args: In the course of touring Alberia as an enka\nsinger, I have experienced a great many\npeople and things.
And one such event involving the boys\nand girls of Quinbell had a brightness not\nunlike sunny skies after a lengthy rain...

Ah, but forgive my getting lost in
recollection in a place like this. You all
appear to be in a most critical moment,
so I will make haste with my report.
I have conducted the secret field survey\nof Alberia you asked of me, Lord Seimei.
From large to small, I have recorded the\nlocation and condition of each and every\ndragon-vein spring in the area. Behold!
You've done well, Rikugo.\nThis should get us somewhere.
The Mukuroshu's goal has always been to\nuse mana from dragon-vein springs to\nopen a gate to the Realm of the Dead.
Doman clearly led us on a merry chase\nand took advantage of the opening it gave\nhim to head for such a spring.
Now hang on just a dad-gummed minute!\nThere's THIS many springs?!
We'd have a better chance to step clean\nthrough a pigsty than we would findin'\nthe exact one where he's at!

Hmph. Use your head, you stupid fox.
We're talking about a spring Doman
would WANT, which means it's both
large and of very high quality.
If we exclude all the smaller dragon-vein\nsprings from our list of potentials,\nthe number is more manageable.
Hoo-eee, but yer noggin is the biggest\nnoggin around, Lord Seimei! Lemme take\na look at that there map... Hrm...
Well, heck. There's still over a hundred\nof the gall-danged things!
She's right. Even with the numbers culled,\ncarefully searching this many springs is\ngoing to be most difficult.
We'll lose the trail if we take much longer.
He's been hiding in the darkness for\nso long...and we are now SO close.
We are going to nail him this time—\nby ANY means necessary!
I understand your feelings, my lord,\nand offer up a suggestion...
Absorb me, and use the power as you will.
I am a high-level shikigami, created by the\nefforts of the onmyoji at the Bureau.

In essence, I am a being of pure mana.
If you absorb me and use it, you could
easily send forth shikigami to a hundred
dragon-vein springs—or even more!
You said by any means necessary.\nWhy do you hesitate?
(Because you're not just any shikigami\nto me, Rikugo...)
(My departed grandfather's mana\nis also a part of you.)
(And that makes you a memento of him.)
This simply isn't like you, Lord Seimei.
Now, I know it is not my place to insist\nyou divulge the things that torment you\nor those better left unsaid...
But you must hold to your resolve.\nThe Seimei I know would always do thus.
Grandfather?! What's wrong?!\nWhat in the world happened?!
Seimei... Be wary... He betrayed us...\nfor the Mukuroshu...

Why hello, Seimei! I owe you a good deal
of thanks, for without your aiding my
research into the fell onmyodo arts,
none of this would have been possible.
Tell me it's not true, Doman! Tell me you\ndidn't use the Kodoku curse on everyone\nin the Bureau!
Ah, but I did EXACTLY that.
But why?! How could you so callously\nsteal away this many lives?!
For power. What possible problem could\nthere be with that?
To master their arts and acquire power is\nthe deeply held desire of any and all with\neven a modicum of talent.
It is because of our shared goal that you\nchose to wash your hands of the other\nBureau onmyoji and aid my research, no?

And now the Kodoku curse has finally
been invoked, thanks to the lives of the
mediocre onmyoji who now serve as
its foundation!
Rejoice, Seimei! This is the spectacle\nwe have strived after for so long!
This hellscape is never what I wanted!
They're all dead, and the responsibility for\nthose deaths all come back to...
Alas, I fear the time has come\nfor us to part, my dear Seimei.
But I will SO be looking forward\nto your coming after me!
For now, each of us must bring out greater\nmastery of our art in the other so that one\nday we might settle this for good and all!
(That day, I swore to pursue him to the\nends of the earth to take my revenge\nfor what he did to Grandfather.)
(It was my mistake to aid his research—\nand as an onmyoji, I have to take\nresponsibility for that.)
(Which is why this must be done!)
Very well, Rikugo. I will use your power.
O ruler of peace and harmony!\nFree thy attendant from his charge and\nguide his power unto me. ...ONMYO!
Do not be sad, friends; mine has always\nbeen a transient existence.
As water flows between sky and earth,\na thing returns to what it must be and\nthe place it must go. That is all this is.
Now, spare not your smiles\nas you see your friend off.
Thank you for your hard work, Rikugo.
We owe ya heaps'n heaps—but we'll make\nsure to catch that nasty Doman and make\nall this here fuss worthwhile!
It is an extremely delightful occasion\nfor one to be hailed by admissions\nof gratitude like drops in a rainstorm...
This... It's all the mana from\nthe Bureau's onmyoji...
Thank you, Rikugo. Thank you, Grandfather.\nI will see this power used for justice!
O creature small of stature. Become my\nlimbs and move with my will! ...ONMYO!
Yee-haw! Don't make no nevermind HOW\nmany springs there is, 'cause we'll have\n'em scouted in two shakes'a my fuzzy tail!
(Incredible... Everything the birds see\nis being sent directly to me...)
Dead to rights—and this time,\nhe's NOT getting away.
